This should be the last of the adaptations.

Utterly trivial follow-up:
I left a few minor comments. Otherwise LGTM.
David, thank you very much for your review!  I accepted/commented on your suggestions.
Utterly trivial follow-up:

This looks great, thanks!
bors d+
Sébastien, thank you very much for your suggestions!  I incorporated them all and explained the one that was not actually supposed to be there.

This one looks pretty bad, since there are two goals, the second of which is data and is constructed while proving the first goal, so in the end there is only one goal. Maybe change it to
```lean
    have : IsUnit (mk' (FractionRing R) x ⟨y, mem_nonZeroDivisors_of_ne_zero hy⟩) := by
      simpa only [isUnit_iff_ne_zero, ne_eq, mk'_eq_zero_iff_eq_zero] using hx
    refine ⟨this.unit, ?_⟩
    rw [mul_comm, ← Units.eq_iff, Units.val_mul, coe_toPrincipalIdeal]
    convert
      (mk'_mul_coeIdeal_eq_coeIdeal (FractionRing R) <| mem_nonZeroDivisors_of_ne_zero hy).2 h
```
(removing the `constructor` line) which is less magical, but not really longer.

Sébastien, thank you for your comment!  I used your version.

While preparing the PR, I tried to be as minimal as possible in the changes, and I (almost) always only changed `·` and indents.

This seems to be a broader rewrite of the proof rather than just focussing / goal-management, and the proof now ends with a terminal "convert" – is there a specific reason for using this in place of `exact` or `apply`?
This one is Sébastien's suggestion from above: neither `apply` nor `exact` work.  I assume it is something to do with typeclasses, but I have not investigated.
Indentation is non-standard here
Good catch: unindented!

Does
```suggestion
  cases' LocalRing.isUnit_or_isUnit_of_add_one this with h' h' <;> [left, right]
```
work?
Yes, I switched to that.
`exact calc` is synonymous with `calc` isn't it?
I am not sure if it is exactly a synonym, but here it worked just as well.

Maybe
```suggestion
      · show f _ = _ by congr 1
      · show g _ = _ by congr 1
```
and kill the last line
It works, and there is no need for the `by`s.

```suggestion
      · show f _ = _; congr 1
```
:facepalm:

This one is weird because it creates two goals, but the second one is closed by closing the first one with `rfl`.
```suggestion
  rw [transAt_indep (Classical.arbitrary N) q, ← fromLoop_trans_toLoop]
  apply Quotient.sound
  rfl
```
is less magical.
Thanks!

Same thing here:
```lean
theorem inv_spec [Nonempty N] {i} {p : Ω^ N X x} : 
    ((⟦p⟧)⁻¹ : HomotopyGroup N X x) = ⟦symmAt i p⟧ := by 
  rw [symmAt_indep (Classical.arbitrary N) p, ← fromLoop_symm_toLoop]
  apply Quotient.sound
  rfl
```
is less magical, but looks really better to me.
Done!
I don't understand this change: it looks to me that there is only one goal, so no need for the focusing dot. Wrong positive of the linter, or is something fishy going on?

You are right, this change does not belong.

This is not even a false positive: at some point, I messed up a git merge and ever since this part of the proof has always created conflicts.  The linter does not flag it and should have fixed this now!
